Diagnosis. Female. Vestiture, head and mesosoma black; metasoma orange (
Fig. 1 a–b
). Lengths: face 4.0– 4.2 mm , scutum 3.2–3.5 mm , forewing 12.0–13.0 mm, body 16.5 –17.0 mm. Structure. Clypeus about three times as wide as long, gently raised above, densely punctuate, ventral edge straight (
Fig. 1 a
); clypeocellus:clypeus 1 : 0.6 ; mandible with 5 teeth, recessed cutting edges in second, third and forth interspaces (
Fig. 1 a
,
2 a
); scopal hairs blunt, not thickened distally.

Male. Vestiture, head, mesosomal venter and metasoma venter pallid (white, pale brown or pale orange), mesosomal dorsum and upper mesepisternum black; legs mostly pallid, middle and hind tarsi black; metasomal dorsum orange (
Fig. 1 c–d
). Lengths: face 3.5–3.7 mm , scutum 2.4–2.6 mm , forewing 9.8 –12.0 mm, body 13.5 –14.1 mm . Structure. Clypeus gently convex above, ventral edge gently concave mediolaterally, weakly tuberculate medially; mandible three apical teeth, one large tooth on ventral edge; foretarsus unmodified; T 6 shield–like, with mediolongitudinal carina, distinctly concave posteromedially, distal margin toothed (
Fig 2 b
); T 7 with mediolongitudinal keel, pointed posteromedially; S 4 with stout, black outer and fine, orange inner tubercles (
Fig. 2 c
); S 6 , S 8 and gonocoxite as illustrated (
Fig. 2 d–f
).

Distribution (
Fig. 3
). Although described from the Cape of Good Hope, which is usually the Cape Town area, this species is otherwise only known in southern Africa from the northern regions of South Africa , except for one record from northern Namibia . Botswana has been poorly collected and it is plausible that there is a continuous distribution from South Africa through Botswana to northern Namibia . The term ‘Cape of Good Hope’ is assumed to have been used generically for the southern African region.
